<!---->
      
<!---->
        <div class="base-aside-card__info self-center pl-1 flex flex-col flex-1">
          <h3 class="base-aside-card__title font-sans text-md font-bold text-color-text relative">
            
<!---->          </h3>

<!---->
            <p class="base-aside-card__subtitle font-sans text-sm text-color-text leading-regular break-words overflow-anywhere
                line-clamp-2">
              
          Technical Engineering Managers Vs Non-Technical Engineering Managers

Off the back of the Tech Leadership London meetups and the work I've done in the London tech markets I've had a number of extremely insightful conversations around the differences in leadership hires. 

The main topic of conversation that I have been having recently is if hands on technical experience is needed for EM level hires. 

Below are 3 conversations I've had in the last weeks:

1. As the Head of Engineering I have been technical throughout my career and my technical skilIs were the reason I was promoted into management. I have now realised that since we have grown and I have direct reports and am not longer hands on I am seeing the benefit of having an exceptional EM on the people side and technical experience is not needed.

2. We have a small product team the EM will be leading and due to some "serious fire fighting" they will need to have a technical background. 

3. As an EM without a hands on technical background the biggest pushback I got from my team was from a Staff Engineer who didn't think I would be able to assist due to a my background. When the engineer eventually left he made a point of citing my work with them as being incredibly beneficial and had completely turned his opinion around.  

There seems to be (like with most topics) quite a divide on this. Start-ups seem to be more likely to want technical skills and those more established teams seeming to value the people skills at a much higher value. 

Thoughts?   
        
            </p>

